Therefore, we have a problem.’ It’s been a blissful week’s holiday on the Côte d’Azur, a perfect antidote to LA, what with the deliciously mouldy cheeses, unashamedly pendulous bare body parts strewn across beaches – and, of course, the refreshing absence of obsequiousness from the service industry. But right now, on a Sunday evening at Toulon airport, I could do with a bit of obsequiousness. I’d even settle for a smidgen of civility. 'My daughter and I have tickets,’ I explain, handing them over to a female Air France clerk (a mother, perhaps?) in the vain hope of sisterly sympathy.
